<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911219-0047</DOCNO><DOCID>911219-0047.</DOCID><HL>   Law:   Keating's Bail Is Cut   To $300,000 by Judge   In Racketeering Case</HL><DATE>12/19/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4</SO><CO>   X-AMC</CO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)LAW AND LEGAL AFFAIRS (LAW)SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS (SAL)</IN><NS>BANKRUPTCY DECLARATIONS AND PROCEEDINGS (BCY)LAW andamp; LEGAL ISSUES AND LEGISLATION (LAW)</NS><GV>FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)</GV><RE>ARIZONA (AZ)CALIFORNIA (CA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   LOS ANGELES -- The judge in Charles H. Keating Jr.'sfederal criminal racketeering and fraud case reduced his bailto $300,000 from $2 million, but Mr. Keating's lawyer saidhis client couldn't post it immediately.   U.S. District Judge Mariana R. Pfaelzer made the rulingafter Mr. Keating submitted a sworn statement listing anegative personal net worth of about $5.5 million. Theonetime chairman of American Continental Corp., who wasindicted on 77 charges last Thursday, remained in custodyyesterday.</LP><TEXT>   Bail for Mr. Keating's son and co-defendant, Charles H.Keating III, was cut to $150,000 from $300,000. The elder Mr.Keating's lawyer, Stephen C. Neal, said the family has atotal of $275,000 in combined equity in three homes and mightnot be able to post a bond to free both men.   Judge Pfaelzer also lowered bail for a third defendant,Judy J. Wischer, to $300,000 from $500,000. Ms. Wischer, aformer president of American Continental, was expected to bereleased immediately on a pledge of property.   At a hearing in federal court here yesterday, assistantU.S. Attorney Alice Hill argued that the Keatings have bothmotive and means to flee. Prosecutors have questioned whathappened to some $8.4 million in American Continental salarythe elder Mr. Keating earned from 1986 to 1989.   In his statement, Mr. Keating denied that he has secretedassets overseas. &quot;I do not own or control any foreign or anyother non de minimis assets that aren't reflected in my Dec.6, 1991, financials or discussed in this declaration,&quot; hewrote.   The federal indictment accuses the defendants of creatingfive separate criminal schemes designed to swindle more than$250 million from American Continental and its former LincolnSavings and Loan Association unit. Mr. Keating was convictedearlier this month on narrower securities fraud charges instate court.</TEXT></DOC>